{"article_id":"znzkWpsRSx63qPAc","edus":[{"id":0,"text":"Washington ( CNN ) -","depth":1},{"id":1,"text":"Despite the flawed rollout of HealthCare.gov ,","depth":5},{"id":2,"text":"a majority of Americans still seem to have an open mind","depth":7},{"id":3,"text":"about whether Obamacare will work ,","depth":7},{"id":4,"text":"and more than half of those surveyed in a new national poll believe","depth":7},{"id":5,"text":"the current problems can be solved .","depth":7},{"id":6,"text":"A CNN/ORC International poll also indicates","depth":8},{"id":7,"text":"nearly six in 10 Americans oppose the national health care law ,","depth":9},{"id":8,"text":"but some give the Affordable Care Act a thumbs down","depth":10},{"id":9,"text":"because it is n't liberal enough .","depth":10},{"id":10,"text":"According to the survey","depth":9},{"id":11,"text":"released on Wednesday ,","depth":9},{"id":12,"text":"four in 10 say","depth":9},{"id":13,"text":"they support the law ,","depth":10},{"id":14,"text":"with 58 % opposed .","depth":10},{"id":15,"text":"Those figures are little changed from a CNN poll a month ago , just two weeks into the rough start up of HealthCare.gov and mostly before the controversy over insurance policy cancellations due primarily to the new health law .","depth":6},{"id":16,"text":"But 41 % say","depth":7},{"id":17,"text":"they oppose the law","depth":8},{"id":18,"text":"because they think","depth":10},{"id":19,"text":"it 's too liberal ,","depth":10},{"id":20,"text":"with 14 % saying","depth":10},{"id":21,"text":"the measure does n't go far enough .","depth":10},{"id":22,"text":"That means that 54 % either support Obamacare ,","depth":8},{"id":23,"text":"or say","depth":9},{"id":24,"text":"it 's not liberal enough .","depth":9},{"id":25,"text":"Nearly four in 10 say","depth":9},{"id":26,"text":"it 's a failure ,","depth":9},{"id":27,"text":"with 53 % saying","depth":9},{"id":28,"text":"it is too soon to tell .","depth":9},{"id":29,"text":"Will the current problems","depth":6},{"id":30,"text":"faced by Obamacare","depth":6},{"id":31,"text":"be eventually solved ?","depth":5},{"id":32,"text":"Fifty-four percent express optimism on this question ,","depth":6},{"id":33,"text":"with 45 % saying","depth":7},{"id":34,"text":"that Obamacare 's flaws will never be fixed .","depth":7},{"id":35,"text":"Younger Americans are much less likely to express negative views of the new health care law .","depth":6},{"id":36,"text":"`` Only 25 % of 18-to-34 year olds say","depth":11},{"id":37,"text":"that the new law is a failure ,","depth":11},{"id":38,"text":"compared to more than four in 10 in any other age bracket .","depth":10},{"id":39,"text":"Seven in 10 younger Americans think","depth":10},{"id":40,"text":"the current problems","depth":12},{"id":41,"text":"faced by Obamacare","depth":12},{"id":42,"text":"will eventually be fixed .","depth":11},{"id":43,"text":"Senior citizens are split ,","depth":9},{"id":44,"text":"and most people between 35 and 65 years old think","depth":10},{"id":45,"text":"that the system is permanently broken , ''","depth":10},{"id":46,"text":"said CNN Polling Director Keating Holland .","depth":7},{"id":47,"text":"The poll was conducted November 18-20 for CNN by ORC International ,","depth":4},{"id":48,"text":"with 843 adult Americans questioned by telephone .","depth":4},{"id":49,"text":"The survey 's overall sampling error is plus or minus 3.5 percentage points .","depth":3}],"relations":[{"parent":99,"left":0,"right":98,"relation":"attribution","nuclearity":"SN"},{"parent":98,"left":95,"right":97,"relation":"context","nuclearity":"NS"},{"parent":95,"left":77,"right":94,"relation":"joint","nuclearity":"NN"},{"parent":77,"left":54,"right":76,"relation":"elaboration","nuclearity":"NS"},{"parent":54,"left":1,"right":53,"relation":"adversative","nuclearity":"SN"},{"parent":53,"left":51,"right":52,"relation":"joint","nuclearity":"NN"},{"parent":51,"left":2,"right":3,"relation":"elaboration","nuclearity":"NS"},